## Beam B

Located on the ground floor. Spans east/west over a hallway to the kitchen and a

![Rafter elevation][]

This house is sufficiently old that its roof framing is not a truss, as would be
done today. Instead, we have rafters that have a strut from their midpoint down
to the ceiling joists. The sketch above shows something that looks like the
bottom chord of a truss, but that doesn’t exist at every roof rafter. The
rafters are placed 2′0′′on center, but the ceiling joists are at 16′′ o.c., so
2/3 of the rafters are not located exactly at a ceiling joist. Instead, all the
kickers land on a plank that runs down the middle of the house on top of the
ceiling joists.

That’s all a bit unusual to the modern eye, but this renovation does not change
the loads placed on the roof or the ceiling joists, so they are grandfathered
in per IEBC section 806.2. We’re here just to substitute some beams for the
existing bearing wall.

The sketch above shows two interior bearing walls. The one on the left is the
one we are replacing with Beam B. The bearing wall shown on the right is a
hallway wall that exists opposite part of Beam B. So the reaction of the
ceiling joists onto Beam B will differ. We’ll get one reaction when the hallway
wall is present and a larger reaction when Beam B has to take all the interior load.

Reaction 1, no hallway wall: Beam B is inline with the interior wall and acts as
the prop in the propped cantilever. So we need to calculate the roof reactions
onto that midpoint hinge and apply it to the propped cantilever. Then we need
